Here is a function in JavaScript that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a valid prime number, if it is print the number to the console.

```javascript
function checkPrimes(arr) {
  for(let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if(isPrime(arr[i])) {
      console.log(arr[i]);
    }
  }
}

function isPrime(num) {
  if(num <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  for(let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    if(num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}
```

The `checkPrimes` function simply iterates over the array and calls the `isPrime` function on each element. If the element is a prime number, it is printed to the console.

The `isPrime` function checks if a number is prime by iterating from 2 to the square root of the number and checking if the number is divisible by any of the numbers in that range. If it is, then it is not a prime number, and the function returns false. If it makes it through the entire loop without finding a divisor, then the number is prime, and the function returns true.

